AB  - In "Memetics and Folkloristics: The Theory" (Oring 2014), the ideas of Richard Dawkins and other memetic theorists were described and critiqued. This essay focuses upon the use of memetics in folkloristics and those substantial attempts to apply memetics to corpuses of folklore or folklore-related problems. Of particular concern are Jack Zipes's memetic explanation of the fairy tale; Bill Ellis's discussion of the viral nature of contemporary legends; Chip Heath et al. 's experiments with urban legend selection; and Michael D. C. Drout's meme-based approach to tradition that focuses on the Benedictine reform in tenth-century Anglo-Saxon England and the "wisdom poems" of the Exeter Book.
