AB  - The paper aims at endorsing key claims made in previous two PhD theses in Computer Science and three papers in social sciences: a) The "e-teaching" component of continuing education can be credibly shaped even for major challenging fields like protecting the environment. b) Continuing education in ecology should be approached transdisciplinary, holistic and following a "logic of action" (process-oriented). c) The main new conceptual pillar (reinforcing those utilized previously: bounded rationality, "Just in Time", and chaoplexity) should be memes. d) A most appropriate tool to test with is a blend of memetics - based on General Systems Theory - and ecolinguistics. Since transdisciplinary work together with ecologists is still nascent, the paper avoids the reservations regarding memetics as ascertained science and even the syntagm "memetic engineering". The conclusions are positive for the first three objectives and promising as regards the experimental model for the last one.
