T2  - 15TH INTERNATIONAL CONGRESS ON CYBERNETICS, PROCEEDINGS
LA  - English
CP  - 15th International Congress on Cybernetics
AB  - History of sciences can be a good sub-field in memetics. I focus on the reception of Darwinism and sociobiology in Japan as case studies, and discuss how to reconstruct history of sciences as a subdivision of memetics. Darwinian evolutionary theory was firstly introduced into Japan during the late 19th century, but was accepted as a theory for social evolution. Even after WW II there was no Darwinism in Japan until 1970s. Then arrived Wilsonian-Dawkinsian sociobiology which broke the Japanese "seclusion" of evolutionary biology during early 1980s. Some preliminary surveys among German-speaking countries and Korean reveals structural and functional similarities as well as dissimilarities to the case in Japan. For a more powerful theory of population memetics, it may be necessary to adopt more concepts from genetics and ecology, as well evolution, e.g., island ecology theory. The fundamentals for analogy building are also required.
