AB  - Using the Dark Brandon meme as a case study, this essay builds on the theoretical frameworks of classical enthymeme, visual argument and Internet memetics to analyze the rhetorical work of an absurd-looking image that became President Joe Biden's reelection poster. The study treats the Dark Brandon meme as a visual enthymeme, whose rhetorical work might paradoxically be both amplified and destabilized by meme logics that define memetic spread and longevity. More specifically, the essay demonstrates how fixity, novelty, resonance and collectivist authorship may both reinforce and detract from the intended reelection arguments.
