TI  - Evolution as a model of design knowledge formation and propagation
T2  - KNOWLEDGE MANAGEMENT FOR INFORMATION COMMUNITIES
LA  - English
CP  - Australian Conference of Knowledge Management and Intelligent Decision Support (ACKMIDS 2000)
AB  - Darwinian evolution provides a paradigmatic foundation for models of the creation, refinement, selection and propagation of knowledge. This paper proposes software design as an example of a knowledge-rich domain and investigates the implications of evolutionary models on the design knowledge processes of this domain. Software engineering has long embraced the idea of evolution in software development processes through prototyping and iterative or recursive design processes, but a broader adoption of biological evolution as a metaphor or model for how 'best practice' software design knowledge establishes and propagates is both new and arguably appealing. One model, memetics, claims to explain the propagation of ideas and the establishment of norms and accepted behaviour patterns in social and professional cultures through the formation of memes - a conceptual equivalent of genes, which are defined as the atoms of information present in all communication domains that compete for survival through selection, modification and propagation by their human hosts. To the degree that memes can be equated with units of design knowledge, the model has some appeal. But the pivotal point upon which the evolutionary analogy balances is the question of where on the scale between vernacular craft (a highly evolutionary design process) and production design (with less scope for design evolution) we place our generalised notion of software design. Despite the influence of methodology and the production metaphor on software development, the craft-like design view continues to have merit in explaining modern software development as practiced, and as long as it does, evolutionary models of software design knowledge have applicability.
